data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The EF Core Cosmos DB provider **removes the sync-over-async opt-in entirely**. In .NET 10 you could suppress the exception, but in EF Core 11 that configuration is gone. Every synchronous LINQ operator throws `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

**All four methods break:**

| Call | Why | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `ToList()` | Sync enumeration removed | `ToListAsync()` |
| `First(...)` | Sync query removed | `FirstAsync(...)` |
| `Count()` | Sync aggregate removed | `CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | Sync persist removed | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

**Fix — make the repository async:**

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

The `Async` methods come from `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore` — make sure you have `using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;` at the top.

**Key point:** this isn't just a surface rename — callers must `await` these methods, so the async change propagates up the call stack (controllers, services, etc.).
